availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: This word is formed out of a "g" with a suspension stroke and a lenition mark; it is not clear what form could be understood here that would require a lenited consonant other than "gho", perhaps modelled on prep. dha.

O'Rahilly (1962: l.4) has "d'innsaighidh" at this point. It seems most probable that "d uinsi" is meant to stand for this, although Mac Mhaighstir Alasdair may have taken it as a description of the world ("duinsith", meaning "fort-peaceful" or suchlike). As this reading is unclear in meaning, and as it is malformed as an attributive genitive in itself (recte "duinsithe"), it is not being included as a possible reading.
This form seems to be based on the genitive of tír, not airther, as if it is being taken as a compound.

This reading of "socht air choraidh" requires socht to have a sense (unattested in eDIL) approximating to "security", "fastening", or suchlike. It also requires an alternative verbal noun (*airchuired) in place of airchor.
